Diversity refers to the presence of differences among people, organisms, or things. In simple terms, it means variety ‚Äî differences in characteristics, traits, or forms within a group or environment.
In biology, diversity (or biodiversity) means the variety of living organisms found in a particular region or on the entire Earth.
It includes differences among plants, animals, microorganisms, and the ecosystems they form.

**In Biology:
Biological diversity (Biodiversity) can be seen at three main levels:
1)Genetic Diversity ‚Äì Variation of genes within a species.
Example: Different varieties of rice or mangoes.

2)Species Diversity ‚Äì Variety of species within a region.
Example: A forest having tigers, elephants, deer, and birds.

3)Ecosystem Diversity ‚Äì Variety of ecosystems in an area.
Example: Deserts, forests, rivers, and mountains.

üåø What is Classification?
Classification in biology is the process of grouping living organisms into categories based on their similarities and differences.
It helps scientists organize, identify, and study the vast diversity of life on Earth in a systematic way.

üéØ Need for Classification
There are millions of living organisms on Earth ‚Äî plants, animals, and microorganisms.
Without classification, studying each organism separately would be impossible.
Hence, classification helps to:
1)Identify and name organisms easily.
2)Understand relationships between different organisms.
3)Study evolution and how life forms are related.

üß† Basis of Classification
Organisms are classified based on several characteristics such as:
Cell structure ‚Äì prokaryotic (without nucleus) or eukaryotic (with nucleus).
Body organization ‚Äì unicellular or multicellular.
Mode of nutrition ‚Äì autotrophic (make own food) or heterotrophic (depend on others).
Reproduction ‚Äì asexual or sexual.
Body design and complexity ‚Äì simple or complex body structures.

| **Level**   | **Description**           | **Example (Human)** |
| ----------- | ------------------------- | ------------------- |
| **Kingdom** | Largest group             | Animalia            |
| **Phylum**  | Group of related classes  | Chordata            |
| **Class**   | Group of related orders   | Mammalia            |
| **Order**   | Group of related families | Primates            |
| **Family**  | Group of related genera   | Hominidae           |
| **Genus**   | Group of related species  | Homo                |
| **Species** | Smallest, specific group  | Homo sapiens        |

Trick to remember:
üëâ King Philip Came Over For Good Soup
(Kingdom ‚Üí Phylum ‚Üí Class ‚Üí Order ‚Üí Family ‚Üí Genus ‚Üí Species)

üåçFive Kingdom Classification (R.H. Whittaker, 1969)
Whittaker proposed a system dividing all organisms into five kingdoms:

| **Kingdom**  | **Examples**               | **Key Features**                          |
| ------------ | -------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| **Monera**   | Bacteria, blue-green algae | Unicellular, prokaryotic                  |
| **Protista** | Amoeba, Paramecium         | Unicellular, eukaryotic                   |
| **Fungi**    | Yeast, Mushroom            | Multicellular, heterotrophic, decomposers |
| **Plantae**  | Algae, Ferns, Trees        | Multicellular, autotrophic                |
| **Animalia** | Humans, Dogs, Fish         | Multicellular, heterotrophic, mobile      |

üß¨ Binomial System of Classification (Binomial Nomenclature)
üåü Introduction
The Binomial System of Classification, also called Binomial Nomenclature, is a method of naming living organisms scientifically using two names.
It was introduced by Carolus Linnaeus in the 18th century.

üìò Meaning
‚ÄúBi‚Äù means two and ‚Äúnomial‚Äù means names.
So, every organism is given two names:
Genus name
Species name
Example:
üëâ Homo sapiens ‚Äî scientific name of humans
Homo ‚Üí Genus
sapiens ‚Üí Species

üî¨ Rules of Binomial Nomenclature (set by ICZN ‚Äì International Code of Zoological Nomenclature)
Each name has two parts ‚Äì Genus and Species.
Genus name starts with a capital letter.
Species name starts with a small letter.
The name should be written in italics (when printed) or underlined separately (when handwritten).
Example: Panthera leo (printed) or Panthera leo (handwritten)
The names are usually in Latin (a universal language for scientists).
Each species has a unique name all over the world.

Eg: of binomial 
| **Common Name** | **Scientific Name**  |
| --------------- | -------------------- |
| Human           | *Homo sapiens*       |
| Mango           | *Mangifera indica*   |
| Tiger           | *Panthera tigris*    |
| Housefly        | *Musca domestica*    |
| Neem            | *Azadirachta indica* |
| Rice            | *Oryza sativa*       |

ü¶† Kingdom Monera ‚Äî Important Points
Includes: All prokaryotic organisms (bacteria and cyanobacteria).
Cell type: Prokaryotic ‚Äî no true nucleus or membrane-bound organelles.
Body organization: Unicellular (single-celled).
Cell wall: Present ‚Äî made of peptidoglycan (murein).
Mode of nutrition:
Autotrophic (make own food) ‚Üí e.g. photosynthetic bacteria.
Heterotrophic (depend on others) ‚Üí e.g. most bacteria.
Mode of reproduction: Asexual, mainly by binary fission.
Genetic material: Single circular DNA, not enclosed in a nucleus.
Examples:
Bacteria (e.g. E. coli, Streptococcus)
Cyanobacteria (blue-green algae, e.g. Anabaena, Nostoc)
Mycoplasma (smallest cell without cell wall).
Habitat: Found everywhere ‚Äî soil, water, air, inside living organisms (ubiquitous).
Importance:
Decomposers ‚Äì recycle nutrients.
Nitrogen fixation ‚Äì Rhizobium, Anabaena.
Used in industries ‚Äì curd, antibiotics, vinegar, etc.
Some cause diseases ‚Äì Typhoid, Tuberculosis.

***KINGDOM PROTISTA:

üß´ Kingdom Protista ‚Äî Important Points
Includes: All unicellular eukaryotic organisms.
Cell type: Eukaryotic ‚Äî true nucleus and membrane-bound organelles present.
Body organization: Unicellular, but some form colonies.
Cell wall: Present in some (like algae), absent in others.
Mode of nutrition:
Autotrophic ‚Üí e.g. Euglena, Diatoms
Heterotrophic ‚Üí e.g. Amoeba, Paramecium
Some are mixotrophic (both) ‚Üí Euglena
Mode of reproduction: Mostly asexual (binary fission) and some sexual.
Movement: Many move using cilia, flagella, or pseudopodia.
Examples:
Amoeba (uses pseudopodia)
Paramecium (uses cilia)
Euglena (has flagellum, shows both plant & animal features)
Diatoms (unicellular algae)
Habitat: Mostly aquatic ‚Äî live in fresh or marine water.
Importance:
Base of aquatic food chain (phytoplankton).
Produce oxygen through photosynthesis.
Some cause diseases ‚Äì e.g. Plasmodium (malaria).

üçÑ Kingdom Fungi ‚Äî Important Points
Cell type: Eukaryotic ‚Äî true nucleus and membrane-bound organelles.
Body organization: Mostly multicellular, but some are unicellular (e.g. Yeast).
Cell wall: Present ‚Äî made of chitin.
Mode of nutrition: Heterotrophic ‚Äì absorb food from outside.
Saprophytic ‚Äì feed on dead matter (e.g. mushrooms).
Parasitic ‚Äì feed on living hosts (e.g. Puccinia).
Symbiotic ‚Äì form partnerships (e.g. lichens, mycorrhiza).
Mode of reproduction:
Asexual ‚Äì by spores, budding, or fragmentation.
Sexual ‚Äì by gamete fusion.
Body structure: Made of thread-like structures called hyphae; network called mycelium.
Examples:
Yeast ‚Äì unicellular, used in baking and alcohol production.
Mushroom ‚Äì saprophytic.
Rhizopus ‚Äì bread mould.
Penicillium ‚Äì source of antibiotic penicillin.
Habitat: Mostly moist and warm places.
Importance:
Decomposers ‚Äì recycle nutrients.
Industrial uses ‚Äì alcohol, bread, antibiotics.
Food ‚Äì mushrooms, yeast.
Some cause diseases ‚Äì ringworm, rust in plants.


üåø Lichens ‚Äî Important Points
Definition:
Lichen is a symbiotic association between a fungus and an alga (or cyanobacterium).
Partners:
Fungus ‚Üí provides water, minerals, and shelter.
Alga ‚Üí prepares food by photosynthesis.

Type of relationship:
Symbiotic (both partners benefit).

Nature of organisms:
Fungus = heterotrophic
Alga = autotrophic

Habitat:
Found on rocks, tree bark, walls, soil, and in harsh conditions (like Arctic or deserts).

Indicator:
Sensitive to air pollution ‚Äî so used as bioindicators of air quality.

Reproduction:
Mostly asexual ‚Äî by fragmentation or spores.

Examples: Usnea,Parmelia,Cladonia
Importance:
Pioneer species in soil formation.
Used in dyes and perfumes.
Indicate clean air (they don‚Äôt grow in polluted areas).
In short:
Lichen = Fungus + Alga (Symbiotic relationship)
Fungus ‚Üí protection üåßÔ∏è
Alga ‚Üí food üåû

üå± Kingdom Plantae ‚Äî Important Points
Cell type: Eukaryotic ‚Äî have a true nucleus and membrane-bound organelles.
Body organization: Mostly multicellular.
Cell wall: Present ‚Äî made of cellulose.
Mode of nutrition: Autotrophic ‚Äî prepare their own food by photosynthesis using chlorophyll.
Reproduction:
Asexual ‚Äì by spores, fragmentation, budding.
Sexual ‚Äì involves formation of gametes.
Stored food: As starch.
Habitat: Found almost everywhere ‚Äî land, water, moist areas.
Movement: Non-motile (do not move).
Body organization: Shows tissue differentiation (roots, stems, leaves, etc.).
Importance:
Produce oxygen and food.
Maintain ecological balance.
Provide medicine, wood, fibers, and shelter.

**Main group of plants based on body and structure:
| **Group**         | **Example**                    | **Key Features**                                          |
| ----------------- | ------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Algae**         | *Spirogyra*, *Chlamydomonas*   | Simple, aquatic, no true roots/stems/leaves               |
| **Bryophytes**    | *Moss*, *Riccia*, *Marchantia* | Amphibians of plant kingdom; need water for fertilization |
| **Pteridophytes** | *Ferns*                        | Have vascular tissues (xylem, phloem), no seeds           |
| **Gymnosperms**   | *Pine*, *Cycas*                | Naked seeds, no fruits or flowers                         |
| **Angiosperms**   | *Rose*, *Mango*, *Wheat*       | Flowering plants with fruits and seeds                    |

**Division based on seeds(Angiosperms)
| **Type**     | **Example**          | **Characteristic**           |
| ------------ | -------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| **Monocots** | *Wheat, Rice, Maize* | One seed leaf (cotyledon)    |
| **Dicots**   | *Pea, Mango, Rose*   | Two seed leaves (cotyledons) |

**Thalophyta:
üåø Thallophyta ‚Äî Important Points
Also called: Algae
Body structure: Thallus-like ‚Äî simple body, no true roots, stems, or leaves.
Cell type: Eukaryotic
Body organization: Multicellular (some unicellular like Chlamydomonas).
Cell wall: Made of cellulose.
Mode of nutrition: Autotrophic ‚Äî prepare food by photosynthesis (contain chlorophyll).
Habitat: Mostly aquatic (freshwater or marine).
Reproduction:
Asexual ‚Äì by fragmentation or spores.
Sexual ‚Äì by fusion of gametes.
Examples: Spirogyra, Ulva, Chlamydomonas, Cladophora.
Importance:
Produce oxygen and form aquatic food base.
Some used as food (e.g. seaweeds).
Used in fertilizers and medicine.

üå≤ Gymnosperms ‚Äî Important Points
Meaning:
‚ÄúGymnosperm‚Äù means ‚Äúnaked seed‚Äù (Greek: gymno = naked, sperma = seed).
‚Üí Seeds are not enclosed in fruits.
Body structure:
Well-developed roots, stems, and leaves (true organs present).
Usually woody plants (trees or shrubs).
Vascular tissue:
Present ‚Äî have xylem and phloem for transport of water and food.
Reproduction:
Do not produce flowers or fruits.
Seeds are naked, found on cone scales.
Pollination: By wind.
Sexual reproduction through male and female cones.
Mode of nutrition: Autotrophic (contain chlorophyll, do photosynthesis).
Habitat: Mostly terrestrial, often found in cold or dry regions.
Examples:
Cycas,Pinus (Pine),Cedrus (Deodar)
Importance:
Provide timber and resin.
Produce turpentine and medicinal compounds.
Show adaptation to extreme conditions.

ü¶ã Kingdom Animalia ‚Äî Important Points
Cell type: Eukaryotic ‚Äî have a true nucleus and membrane-bound organelles.
Cell wall: Absent (unlike plants and fungi).
Body organization: Multicellular organisms with complex tissues and organs.
Mode of nutrition: Heterotrophic ‚Äî depend on others for food (ingest and digest food).
Movement: Most are motile (can move using muscles).
Reproduction:
Mainly sexual, some show asexual reproduction.
Development may include larval stages.
Nervous system: Well developed in most animals for coordination and response.
Habitat: Found in all environments ‚Äî land, water, air.
Symmetry:
Some asymmetrical (e.g. Sponges).
Most bilaterally or radially symmetrical.
Vascular system: Absent, but have circulatory and respiratory systems in complex animals.
üêö Classification of Animal Kingdom (Major Phyla)
Phylum / Group	Example	Key Feature
Porifera	Sponges	Pores on body, no true tissues or organs
Coelenterata (Cnidaria)	Hydra, Jellyfish	Radial symmetry, tentacles, stinging cells
Platyhelminthes	Tapeworm	Flat worms, first to show bilateral symmetry
Nematoda	Ascaris	Round worms, body unsegmented
Annelida	Earthworm, Leech	Segmented body, true coelom
Arthropoda	Insects, Crabs	Jointed legs, exoskeleton of chitin, largest phylum
Mollusca	Snail, Octopus	Soft body, may have shell
Echinodermata	Starfish	Marine, spiny skin, radial symmetry in adults
Chordata	Fish, Birds, Humans	Notochord or backbone present

üßΩ Phylum Porifera ‚Äî Important Points
Common name: Sponges
Habitat: Aquatic, mostly marine (live in sea water).
Body organization: Cellular level (no true tissues or organs).
Body structure:
Full of pores (tiny holes) for water circulation ‚Äî hence name Porifera (‚Äúpore bearers‚Äù).
Body supported by spicules or spongin fibres.
Symmetry: Asymmetrical (no definite shape).
Coelom: Absent.
Circulation & digestion: Water enters through pores ‚Üí brings food & oxygen ‚Üí exits through a large opening (osculum).
Mode of nutrition: Filter feeders (get food from water passing through body).
Reproduction:
Asexual ‚Äì by fragmentation or budding.
Sexual ‚Äì formation of gametes.
Examples:
Sycon,Spongilla (freshwater),Euspongia (bath sponge).

üåä Phylum Coelenterata (Cnidaria) ‚Äî Important Points
Common name: Cnidarians or Coelenterates
Habitat: Aquatic, mostly marine.
Body organization: Tissue level (first animals to show true tissues).
Body symmetry: Radial symmetry (body parts arranged around a central axis).
Body structure:
Hollow, sac-like body with a single opening (mouth).
Have tentacles with stinging cells (cnidoblasts or nematocysts) for capturing prey and defense.
Coelom: Absent (acoelomate).
Mode of nutrition: Heterotrophic, carnivorous (capture small animals using tentacles).
Reproduction:
Asexual ‚Äì by budding (e.g. Hydra).
Sexual ‚Äì by gamete formation.
Show alternation of generations (polyp and medusa forms).
Examples:
Hydra,Jellyfish (Aurelia),Sea anemone,Corals.

**Phylum Platyhelminthes ‚Äî Important Points
Body type: Flat, soft, ribbon-like body ‚Äî bilaterally symmetrical and triploblastic.
Body organization: Organ level ‚Äî have true organs but no body cavity (acoelomate).
Habitat: Mostly parasitic (live inside other animals); some are free-living.
Reproduction: Mostly hermaphrodite (male & female organs in same body).
Examples: Planaria (free-living), Tapeworm, Liver fluke (parasitic).

**üß¨ Phylum Nematoda ‚Äî Important Points
Body type: Long, cylindrical, unsegmented body; bilateral symmetry and triploblastic.
Body cavity: Pseudocoelomate (false body cavity).
Habitat: Mostly parasitic in humans and animals; some are free-living in soil or water.
Digestive system: Complete ‚Äî has both mouth and anus.
Examples: Ascaris (roundworm), Wuchereria (causes elephantiasis), Ancylostoma (hookworm).

**| **Feature**               | **Annelida**                              | **Arthropoda**                                    |
| ------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| **1. Body type**          | Segmented, soft, cylindrical body         | Segmented body with **jointed legs**              |
| **2. Skeleton**           | **No exoskeleton** (body soft)            | **Hard exoskeleton** made of **chitin**           |
| **3. Body cavity**        | **True coelomate**                        | **Coelomate**                                     |
| **4. Circulatory system** | **Closed circulation** (blood in vessels) | **Open circulation** (blood flows in body cavity) |
| **5. Examples**           | *Earthworm*, *Leech*, *Nereis*            | *Cockroach*, *Crab*, *Butterfly*, *Spider*        |


| **Feature**           | **Mollusca**                              | **Pisces (Fish)**  | **Amphibia**                          | **Reptilia**                           | **Mammalia**                   |
| --------------------- | ----------------------------------------- | ------------------ | ------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| **1. Body covering**  | Soft body with **shell** (mostly calcium) | **Scales** on skin | **Moist skin** (no scales)            | **Dry, scaly skin**                    | **Hair or fur** on skin        |
| **2. Habitat**        | Mostly **aquatic**                        | **Aquatic**        | **Both land & water**                 | **Terrestrial**                        | **Terrestrial** (some aquatic) |
| **3. Respiration**    | **Gills** or **lungs**                    | **Gills**          | **Gills (larva)** & **lungs (adult)** | **Lungs only**                         | **Lungs only**                 |
| **4. Heart chambers** | Variable (mostly 2)                       | **2-chambered**    | **3-chambered**                       | **3-chambered** (except crocodile ‚Äì 4) | **4-chambered**                |
| **5. Examples**       | *Octopus*, *Snail*, *Pila*                | *Rohu*, *Shark*    | *Frog*, *Toad*                        | *Lizard*, *Snake*, *Turtle*            | *Human*, *Cow*, *Dog*, *Whale* |

